# PAI-700: allowlisted gitleaks findings.
#
# Each entry is a fingerprint: <commit>:<file>:<rule-id>:<line>. The commits
# are immutable, so these fingerprints are stable — they do not drift when
# later edits move lines around.
#
# Why fingerprints and not a path rule: exempting `*_test.go` wholesale would
# also hide a REAL credential pasted into a test file. These four entries
# forgive four specific historical matches and nothing else.
#
# Why not a gitleaks baseline file: baseline output embeds the matched secret
# values, which would commit them to the repo. Fingerprints carry no value.
#
# Triage (2026-07-24). All four are matches of the upstream `generic-api-key`
# rule — NOT the custom `paimos-api-key` rule — against 8-character, non-hex
# string literals in test files. Real PAIMOS API keys are `paimos_` + 64 hex
# chars, so an 8-char non-hex literal cannot be one. Context confirms
# fixtures: `writeServeFixture(t, root, ...)`, `plaintext := []byte(...)`,
# and test POST bodies.
#
# These were never scanned by CI before PAI-700: the workflow ran gitleaks
# with `--log-opts=-1`, i.e. the tip commit only, despite a comment claiming
# full history. Three of the four postdate the "verified clean as of
# 2026-04-26" note in ci-v2.yml.

